SIMPLE: fifteenth
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fifteenth
<hw>Fif"teenth`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fiftenthe</ets>; cf. <ets>fiftethe</ets>, AS.
<ets>f⟦imac⟧fte⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧a</ets>. See <er>Fifteen</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Next in order after the fourteenth; -- the ordinal of
fifteen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consisting of one of fifteen equal parts or
divisions of a thing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fifteenth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fifteenth
<hw>Fif"teenth`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of fifteen
equal parts or divisions; the quotient of a unit divided by
fifteen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A species of tax upon personal property formerly
laid on towns, boroughs, etc., in England, being one fifteenth part of
what the personal property in each town, etc., had been valued at.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A stop in an organ
tuned two octaves above the diaposon.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An
interval consisting of two octaves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fifth</ent>⟦br⟧
